http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=216287&amp;alt=46269</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raiddinn>Raiddinn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Minstrel</span><br>  Posts: 291<br> <font color=#330000>(7/1/04 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19552.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ~</span><hr size=1> Actually, my views differ slightly from a lot of those earlier expressed.<br>
<br>
First of all, DS on the MT is not a factor, I can count on about 1 hand all the times that DS from me really affected the outcome of the fights, also note that if some random guild wanted another wiz worth of DPS they could just recruit another wiz.....<br>
<br>
DS never helps a MT do his MT job ever in any way.  If DS is a bonus from a song thats meant for other reasons (veeshan) then thats good, but otherwise no consideration needs to be given to DS on the MT, save that stuff for mages and the shaman potion market, if the MT is so inclined.<br>
<br>
Bards job is to make sure people can do their job, and when its a bard in the MT group its his job to make sure the MT can MT and keep MTing.<br>
<br>
To make sure a MT can MT and keep MTing, imho these songs are useful.<br>
Nivs +ac<br>
Veeshan resist/ac<br>
cha song for DI<br>
rizlona overhaste<br>
<br>
+AC is a no brainer for MTs, the difference between having and not having like 150 ac is pretty large damage mitigation wise.<br>
<br>
Veeshan - better chance to resist a proc or AE is always good, I cant count the number of times I have resisted procs that are nearly lure with 500 resist all (1 buff and 1 song)<br>
<br>
Cha song, I am a big believer in this, clerics take themselves out of the chain to cast DI so it must be useful.  We are a guild with pretty good healing power though and dropping from the chain to DI has been beneficial for us.  Might as well help it work if they are going to drop from the chain to cast it.<br>
<br>
Lastly, Rizlona.  This is a situational dependant song, with very few situations where its really good to use, but in those situations it can be very powerful.<br>
<br>
First of all you have to consider, when rizlona is sung is it going to make the MT die from the extra ripostes?  If the MT is outside of a defensive/evasive/stonewall/cantrememberripostedisk then probably its not worth it.<br>
<br>
However, during those disks where the chance to die from ripostes is much lower, sometimes the benefit of having more aggro on the MT can outdo the value of something thats made situationally worse while the MT is in those disks, namely CHA for DI.  In our raids with our MTs in against the various EP mobs, our MTs never get under half while in disks, which would make CHA song a non factor in those cases, even with rizlona the tanks dont go under half from ripostes, and it gives them some nice extra aggro (we have lots of overnukers).<br>
<br>
Of course when disk goes down then switch to CHA over rizlona since in that case the benefits of CHA will outweigh the benefit of rizlona which has turned into a possible drawback.<br>
<br>
Impressario Raiddinn the Beatdropper<br>
65/375 Maestro Rallos Zek <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p201.ezboard.com/btheconcerthall.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wyndaria>wyndaria</A></span><br> Posts: 277<br> <font color=#330000>(7/1/04 12:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19552.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: When to use Nivs Harmonic?</span><hr size=1> I typically bow to the wisdom of bards who have more experience than I do, and are generally much further in the game.  However, I am a little skeptical of some of the claims about the power of AC when played by bards. <br>
<br>
Let me explain...<br>
<br>
There were some very good posts a while back on Steel Warrior (done by brutaal?) with lots of VERY long AC vs mob DPS parses...  basically, in the end, it went something like this:<br>
<br>
1550-2150 AC = 600 AC delta gave 15% mitigation. <br>
<br>
And, recently, there have been some posts by EQ devs that clearly say that there are some effective AC caps against attack (see the posts about the effectiveness of shields) that do limit how much AC really helps past a certain point.<br>
<br>
But for now, let's just assume that a 2500 AC war isn't really at the cap (even though they may be).  Let's also assume that the effect of AC is linear (which it's not), so that each additional 100AC gives 2.5% mitigation. <br>
<br>
So, a Time capable bard, focusing 100% of their effort, with completely maxed AA's, and max instrument mods, can add 189 AC (thanks Pling).  Let's be generous and round it up to 200...  So, the best bard in the game currently is gonna add...  drum roll please...<br>
<br>
5% mitigation.  <br>
<br>
Yep, that's it.  5%!  <br>
<br>
Now, i know 5% adds up on top of everything else, extra hps, extra resists, and all that and it's nothing to sneeze about.  However, the general euphoria around bard AC songs in the MT group due to so much AC is unjustified.  It's highly dubious  that it would make an event doable when it wasn't before. <br>
<br>
Heck, I would guess, given the lengths of most fights, that when you factor in the RNG, 5% mitigation is not even statistically measurable.  And, nevermind that most bards couldn't even begin to approach that number, and are much closer to about 2% when all is said and done. <br>
<br>
And, that's all I have to say about that...<br>
 <p>Wyndaria, <br>
Maestro, The Nameless.<br>
